      <hedline>
        <hl1>Voting For or Against War</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rev Larry L Greenfield letter, prompted by Adam Cohen Jan 29 Editorial Observer on Congress's war powers, says Congress alone has power to declare war, and it has not yet done so, so legislators should vote now on whether to wage war against Iraq</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Congress, the Constitution and War: The Limits on Presidential Power,'' by Adam Cohen (Editorial Observer, Jan. 29):</p>
        <p>There is a straightforward way to continue or terminate American involvement in the Iraqi conflict. Since Congress alone has the power to declare war, and because it has not yet done so, legislation should now be submitted on a declaration of war.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Congress, the Constitution and War: The Limits on Presidential Power,'' by Adam Cohen (Editorial Observer, Jan. 29):</p>
        <p>There is a straightforward way to continue or terminate American involvement in the Iraqi conflict. Since Congress alone has the power to declare war, and because it has not yet done so, legislation should now be submitted on a declaration of war.</p>
        <p>If the legislation passed, the president would continue to fulfill his obligations as commander in chief. If it was defeated, the president would be constitutionally obligated to terminate our involvement in Iraq, presumably in the most direct and orderly manner.</p>
        <p>Why delay a decision that the Constitution directs Congress to make?</p>
        <p>(Rev.) Larry L. Greenfield  Pesotum, Ill., Jan. 30, 2007</p>
      </block>
